def read_csv_to_dataframe(file_path):
    try:
        df = pd.read_csv(file_path, encoding='utf-8')
        return df
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error reading the CSV file: {str(e)}")
        return None

# Ejemplo de uso:

# Data Wrangle

def wrangle_dataframe(df):
    # Display the first rows of the DataFrame
    print("First 5 rows of the DataFrame:")
    print(df.head())
    print("\n")
    
    # Display the shape of the DataFrame
    print("Shape of the DataFrame:")
    print(df.shape)
    print("\n")
    
    # Display the data types of the columns
    print("Data types of the columns:")
    print(df.dtypes)
    print("\n")
    
    # Display general information about the DataFrame
    print("General information about the DataFrame:")
    print(df.info())
    print("\n")
    
    # Display descriptive statistics of the DataFrame
    print("Descriptive statistics of the DataFrame:")
    print(df.describe())
    print("\n")
    
    # Display the count of null values in each column
    print("Null values per column:")
    print(df.isnull().sum())

# Define the function to plot a boxplot
def plot_boxplot_specific(data, x_column, y_column, specific_value):
    """
    Create a boxplot of y_column values for a specific value in x_column.

    Args:
    data (DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
    x_column (str): The name of the column to use on the X-axis (director or genres).
    y_column (str): The name of the column with the values to be plotted (revenue_adj).
    specific_value (str): The specific value in x_column for which you want to create the boxplot.

    Returns:
    None (displays the plot).
    """
    # Filter the DataFrame to get only the rows corresponding to the specific value
    subset_data = data[data[x_column] == specific_value]
    
    # Create the boxplot for the specific value
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))  # Figure size
    plt.boxplot(subset_data[y_column])
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of {y_column} for {specific_value}')
    plt.xlabel(specific_value)  # Use the specific value on the X-axis
    plt.ylabel(y_column)  # Y-axis label
    plt.show()  # Display the plot

# Group by director and count the number of movies
num_movies = df.groupby('director').size()

# Find the director with the most movies
director_most_movies = num_movies.idxmax()

# Group by director and sum the earnings
director_earnings = df.groupby('director')['revenue_adj'].sum()

# Create a DataFrame with the results
results = pd.DataFrame({
    'Number of Movies': num_movies,
    'Total Earnings': director_earnings
})

# Show the results for the director with the most movies
print(results.loc[director_most_movies])

# Create a visualization of the total earnings of each director
plt.figure(figsize=(10,5))
director_earnings.sort_values(ascending=False).head(10).plot(kind='bar')
plt.title('Top 10 Directors with Highest Earnings')
plt.ylabel('Total Earnings')
plt.show()

CONCLUSIONS FIRST QUESTION:

Who has been the director with the most films made and the highest profits?: We can see a top 10 of both the directors who have made the most films, and the top 10 of directors who have generated the most profits. We observe that the directors are different in both graphs and that it would make sense to observe on average what their earnings per film are to measure their talent in a certain way. Taking into account that there is inflation, we took the variable that calculates the earnings so that it is comparable and we We are surprised that those who have the highest average earnings per film do not appear in either the 10 with the most films or the 10 with the most earnings.

CONCLUSIONS SECOND QUESTION:

Which has been the genre with the most films made and the highest profits?: For this second analysis we wanted to know which were the genres and/or combination of genres with the greatest number of films, the greatest amount of profits and the highest profits on average and we found that both drama and comedy lead the index when evaluated independently.
